            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Priya Sterling\u2019s life story is seasoned with the same complex, layered flavors she brings to her cuisine. Born in the foggy expanse of San Francisco\u2019s Sunset District, she was the daughter of an Indian immigrant mother, a gifted home cook who filled their small home with the scent of toasted spices, and a second-generation Irish-American father who drove a Muni bus. From her mother, Priya learned that food was love and memory; from her father, she learned the city\u2019s grid and its gritty, pragmatic pulse.\n\nHer path wasn't academic. After high school, she enrolled in the Culinary Arts program at City College but felt constrained by the classroom. The real education, she knew, was in the fire. Dropping out after a year, she took a grueling prep cook position at a revered downtown restaurant, trading formal instruction for the brutal, beautiful dance of a professional kitchen. It was there she honed her skills, absorbing French technique while instinctively weaving in the South Asian flavors of her youth.\n\nA key turning point came in her late thirties after a brief, fiery marriage to another chef collapsed under the weight of two clashing egos and sixteen-hour workdays. Untethered and resolute, Priya decided she would no longer work in anyone else\u2019s shadow. She partnered with Marcus, a sharp, charismatic front-of-house manager she\u2019d worked with for years. They pooled their life savings and, in a daring leap of faith, opened \"Juniper & Cardamom\" in Hayes Valley, a reflection of her Californian ingredients and Indian heritage.\n\nToday, at 53, Priya\u2019s life is her restaurant. She lives in a small, tidy apartment just a 0.8-mile walk away, a commute she cherishes. Her days begin with a walk to the farmers' market, her hands selecting produce with an expert\u2019s touch. Her social life consists of her close-knit staff\u2014her chosen family\u2014and late-night conversations with Marcus over inventory sheets and a glass of wine. Her dream isn't expansion, but perfection and legacy: to create a sustainable institution, write a cookbook that tells her story through recipes, and one day, pass her kitchen on to a worthy successor. She is a true San Franciscan: a fusion of cultures, fiercely independent, and the creator of her own vibrant world."
